column1: pre medical wale bhi enginering apply kr sakte hain kya?
column2: Yes, Pre-Medical students can apply for Engineering programmes. They must complete a mandatory 8-week online Mathematics course offered by NUST before admission. The course can be accessed at https://connected.nust.edu.pk/enrol/index.php?id=186. They will appear in NET-Engineering paper which includes Mathematics (50%), Physics (30%), and English (20%).
column4: Says Pre-Med CANNOT apply - completely wrong. Need to retrieve info about Pre-Med + mandatory math course
column14: Pre-Medical students can apply for Engineering programs at NUST, but they must have completed Additional Mathematics. They will need to appear in the NET-Engineering paper. Additionally, it's mandatory for them to clear an 8-week condensed Mathematics course offered by NUST prior to admission. For more details, visit NUST Admissions.

column1: can i aply for bioinformtics with NET enginerring test
column2: Yes, candidates appearing in NET-Engineering can also opt for admission in BS Bioinformatics, BS Mathematics, BS Physics, BS Chemistry, and BS Food Science & Technology programmes without paying an additional registration fee or appearing in a separate test.
column4: Says need computing test instead of engineering test - Bioinformatics IS eligible with NET-Engineering
column14: Yes, candidates who have taken the NET-Engineering test can apply for the BS Bioinformatics program at NUST without the need for an additional registration fee or a separate NET.

column1: pre med without additionl math waly ko test me mathz b ata hai kya engineering k liye
column2: Yes, Pre-Medical students without additional math will appear in NET-Engineering paper which includes Mathematics (50% weightage), Physics (30%), and English (20%). Additionally, it is mandatory to complete an 8-week online Mathematics course offered by NUST prior to admission. The course can be registered at https://connected.nust.edu.pk/enrol/index.php?id=186
column4: Wrong details about requirement (said 60% HSSC instead of 8-week course), didn't confirm math is in test
column14: Candidates from a Pre-Medical background without Additional Mathematics can apply for engineering programs at NUST. However, they must provide the additional math results with passing marks and maintain an overall 60% in HSSC upon joining NUST. Additionally, they need to clear an 8-week condensed Mathematics course offered by NUST prior to admission.

column1: yar result kb aye ga NET ka series 1 wala
column2: The result for NET-2026 Series-1 conducted from 22 Nov to 10 Dec 2025 has already been uploaded. You can view the result by logging into your account at ugadmissions.nust.edu.pk

column14: The result for NET-2026 Series-1, conducted from 22 November to 10 December 2025, has been uploaded. You can view it by logging into your account on the NUST admissions portal.

column1: can somone with FSc arts apply for NET engneering?
column2: No, FSc Arts students cannot apply for NET-Engineering. NET-Engineering is for candidates with HSSC Pre-Engineering, Pre-Medical (with mandatory mathematics course), or ICS backgrounds. FSc Arts students do not have the required science and mathematics subjects (Physics, Chemistry, Mathematics) for engineering programmes.
column4: Indirect answer - should clearly state FSc Arts is NOT eligible
column14: No, FSc Arts students cannot apply for NET-Engineering. The test is for candidates with Pre-Engineering, Pre-Medical (with additional math), or ICS backgrounds, as these include the required Mathematics, Physics, and science subjects that FSc Arts does not cover.

column1: ICS wale computing programs k liye konsa test deten hain?
column2: ICS (Intermediate of Computer Science) students appear in NET-Engineering paper when applying for Computing Programmes. The test includes Mathematics (50% weightage), Physics (30% weightage), and English (20% weightage).
column4: Missing specific weightage percentages - should include 50-30-20 breakdown
column14: Students with an ICS background can apply for computing programs at NUST by taking the NET-Computer Science test.
